SIMPLE: submit
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Submit
<hw>Sub*mit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Submitted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Submitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>submittere</ets>; <ets>sub</ets> under + <ets>mittere</ets> to
send: cf. F. <ets>soumettre</ets>. See <er>Missile</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To let down; to lower.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sometimes the hill <qex>submits</qex> itself a while.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put or place under.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The bristled throat⟦br⟧
Of the <qex>submitted</qex> sacrifice with ruthless steel he cut.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To yield, resign, or surrender to power, will, or
authority; -- often with the reflexive pronoun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye ben <qex>submitted</qex> through your free assent.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The angel of the Lord said unto her, Return to thy mistress, and
<qex>submit</qex> thyself under her hands.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xvi.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wives, <qex>submit</qex> yourselves unto your own husbands.</q>
<rj><qau>Eph. v. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To leave or commit to the discretion or judgment of
another or others; to refer; <as>as, to <ex>submit</ex> a controversy to
arbitrators; to <ex>submit</ex> a question to the court</as>; -- often
followed by a dependent proposition as the object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether the condition of the clergy be able to bear a heavy
burden, is <qex>submitted</qex> to the house.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>submit</qex> that a wooden spoon of our day would not be
justified in calling Galileo and Napier blockheads because they never
heard of the differential calculus.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Submit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Submit
<hw>Sub*mit"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To yield one's
person to the power of another; to give up resistance; to
surrender.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The revolted provinces presently <qex>submitted</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>C. Middleton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To yield one's opinion to the opinion of authority
of another; to be subject; to acquiesce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To thy husband's will⟦br⟧
Thine shall <qex>submit</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be submissive or resigned; to yield without
murmuring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our religion requires from us . . . to <qex>submit</qex> to pain,
disgrace, and even death.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Submitter</ent>⟦br⟧
